 by moving crops to more favourable areas and by agronomic tweaks but that will almost certainly not be enough we will have to give crops a genetic helping hand infusing them with new genes to allow them to better cope with new climates and the new pests and diseases they will bring where are these genes going to come from download html+ go to site external http www nature com nclimate jour parent events adapting agriculture to climate change the role of crop wild relatives september 6 2010 september 10 2010 fsi stanford fse conference parent research climate and agriculture models impacts and adaptation strategies prioritizing investments in food security under a changing climate fsi stanford fse project topics agricultural adaptation and climate change climate change search fsi search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages publication news greater crop diversity and wild genes needed to feed growing population october 28 2011 fsi stanford fse news publications of interest effects of aquaculture on world fish supplies rosamond l naylor rebecca j goldberg jurgenne primavera nils kautsky malcolm cm beveridge jason clay carl folke jane lubchenco harold mooney max troell nature vol 405 6790 2000 html+ cover fugitive salmon assessing the risks of escaped fish from net pen aquaculture rosamond l naylor kjetil hindar ian a fleming rebecca goldberg susan williams john volpe fred whoriskey josh eagle dennis kelso marc mangel bioscience vol 55 5 2005 html+ cover candidates views on science the donald kennedy science vol 290 5490 2000 html+ cover on the regulation of geo engineering david g victor oxford review of economic policy vol 24 2 2008 html+ pdf+ cover support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 4581 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
